General color in fresh specimens brown suffused with testaceous (older specimens pale yellow) (

Fig. 
1

). Vertex brown with testaceous spots. Eyes dark brown. Frons brown with apex dark brown (

Fig. 
2

). Pronotum and mesoscutellum brown with some testaceous maculae on disc (

Fig. 
1

). Tegmen brown with veins testaceous (
Figs 1, 3
); wing dark brown (

Fig. 
1

). Legs brown, hind femora and base of hind tibia dark brown (

Fig. 
3

). Abdomen brown with disc dark brown, apex reddish-brown.

Head very long, tapering to apex; apex of vertex upturned in lateral view (
Fig. 3
). Vertex more or less triangular with median carina, narrow with disc slightly convex, 3.3 × longer in midline than width at apex (
Fig. 1
). Frons smooth, with median carina apparent only along one third of midline; disc elevated, widest near eyes, 1.8 × wider at widest part than at base, and midlength 2.9 × longer than greatest width (
Fig. 2
). Frontoclypeal suture arched (
Fig. 2
). Clypeus small with median carina; clypeus and the base of frons at same plane in lateral view (
Fig. 2
). Pedicel of antenna large and nearly tubular, with many scattered sensilla (
Fig. 8
). Pronotum wide with anterior margin distinctly convex and hind margin nearly straight, disc with many irregular pale ivory tubercles (
Fig. 1
). Mesoscutellum nearly triangular, disc with two dark spots, 1.9 × wider at widest part than medial length (
Fig. 1
). Tegmen nearly elliptical; veins elevated, longitudinal veins with many short cross veins, 2.4 × longer than widest part; Sc long, reaching past the middle, M 2 branched, Cu not forked, an extra vein arising after apex of clavus nearly parallel to Cu ( Figs 1 , 9 ). Wing large with two lobes, veins reticulate, 0.95 × length of tegmen (
Fig. 10
). Hind tibia with two lateral teeth near apex (
Fig. 3
). Spinal formula of hind leg
7–11 – 2 .

Male genitalia
: Anal segment moderately large, mushroom-shaped, longer than medial width in dorsal view (

Fig. 
12

); lateral margin strongly convex, apical margin slightly concave with angles obtuse; ventral margin a little convex in lateral view (

Fig. 
11

). Anal tube situated basally (

Fig. 
12

). Pygofer slightly longer ventrally than dorsally in profile; dorsocaudal angle distinctly produced and tapered basally (

Fig. 
11

). Connective fused with aedeagus. Aedeagus curved downward medially near apex (
Figs 13, 14
). Aedeagus somewhat U-shaped, symmetrical, with two moderately long, spiniform processes and lateral, ventral and dorsal lobes (
Figs 13, 14
); dorsal lobe bifurcate with apical margin rounded, convex in middle in dorsal view, apex tapering, enveloping lateral lobes and ventral lobe downwards; lateral lobes branched with apex slender and obtuse in lateral view (

Fig. 
13

); ventral lobe not divided, apical margin a little concave, apex obtuse in ventral view (

Fig. 
14

). Genital styles moderately long with process in lateral view; apex of process tapering and hooked (

Fig. 
11

).

Female genitalia : Anal segment in dorsal view (
Fig. 16
) distinctly longer than maximum width, with lateral margins nearly straight, and apical margin convex; in lateral view (
Fig. 15
) relatively narrow basally with apex slightly curved downward and rounded, dorsal margin sinuate; apex rounded with ventral margin nearly straight. Ovipositor (
Fig. 15
) with first valvula curved dorsally, with three nearly parallel teeth. Third valvula stout, strongly convex, nearly triangular, with apical margin tumid and polished. Pregenital sternite with apical margin distinctly convex (
Fig. 17
).

Remarks.
This species superficially resembles 

Choutagus longicephalus

Zhang, Wang and Che, 
2006


(

Figs 
4– 7

) (Hemisphaeriinae), but can be distinguished from the latter by: 
1
) tegmen with claval suture; 
2
) the wing is bisected into two lobes; 
3
) the apex of vertex upcurved in lateral view; 
4
) vertex, frons and clypeus without lateral carinae, and pronotum and mesoscutellum without median or lateral carinae.

Pseudochoutagus curvativus

sp. nov.
is related to 

Thabena retracta
(

Walker, 
1857

)

(
Issini
), but the main differences are: 
1
) vertex with apex upcurved in lateral view (nearly horizontal in 

Thabena retracta

); 
2
) disc of pronotum with many irregular pale ivory tubercles (without tubercles in 

Thabena retracta

); 
3
) spiniform processes of aedeagus smooth and not bearing denticles on external margins (bearing denticles in 

Thabena retracta

).
